          "title": "Algorithms with Selection and Repetition",
          "unit": 2,
          "source": "Unit2_Detailed_Tutorials.md",
          "body": "### What You Are Learning\n\nYou are learning how to represent algorithms that choose between paths and repeat steps.\n\n### Mental Model\n\nSelection asks:\n\n```text\nShould this block run?\n```\n\nIteration asks:\n\n```text\nShould this block run again?\n```\n\n### Everyday Example\n\nAlgorithm for studying:\n\n```text\nIf score is below 70, review the topic.\nRepeat practice questions until 5 questions are correct in a row.\n```\n\nSelection: \"If score is below 70\"\n\nIteration: \"Repeat until 5 correct in a row\"\n\n### Java Pattern\n\n```java\nif (score < 70)\n{\n    topic = \"Review\";\n}\n\nwhile (streak < 5)\n{\n    practice();\n}\n```\n\n### Common Mistakes\n\n- Writing vague algorithms that skip important details.\n- Forgetting to say when repetition stops.\n- Mixing up a one-time decision with repeated checking.\n\n### Practice\n\nWrite an English algorithm for:\n\n1. Counting the number of even integers from 1 through 100.\n2. Finding the first passing score in a list.\n3. Asking for input until the user enters a positive number."
