          "id": "2.6",
          "title": "Comparing Boolean Expressions",
          "unit": 2,
          "source": "Unit2_Detailed_Tutorials.md",
          "body": "### What You Are Learning\n\nYou are learning equivalent forms of logic.\n\n### De Morgan's Laws\n\n```java\n!(a && b)  is equivalent to  !a || !b\n!(a || b)  is equivalent to  !a && !b\n```\n\n### Truth Tables\n\nTwo Boolean expressions are equivalent only if they produce the same result for every possible combination of inputs.\n\n| `a` | `b` | `a && b` | `!(a && b)` | `!a || !b` |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| false | false | false | true | true |\n| false | true | false | true | true |\n| true | false | false | true | true |\n| true | true | true | false | false |\n\nBecause the last two columns always match, `!(a && b)` is equivalent to `!a || !b`.\n\n### Examples\n\n```java\n!(score >= 70)\n```\n\nEquivalent:\n\n```java\nscore < 70\n```\n\n```java\n!(x > 0 && y > 0)\n```\n\nEquivalent:\n\n```java\nx <= 0 || y <= 0\n```\n\n### Comparing Objects\n\nFor strings:\n\n```java\nword.equals(\"yes\")\n```\n\nNot:\n\n```java\nword == \"yes\"\n```\n\nFor object references, `==` checks whether two references point to the same object.\n\n### Comparing With `null`\n\nUse `==` or `!=` to test whether a reference actually points to an object.\n\n```java\nif (student != null)\n{\n    System.out.println(student.getName());\n}\n```\n\nDo the null check before calling an instance method. Calling a method on `null` causes a `NullPointerException`.\n\n### Class-Specific `equals`\n\nMany classes define their own `equals` method to compare meaningful attributes.\n\n```java\nword.equals(\"yes\")\n```\n\nchecks text content for `String` objects. AP CSA expects students to understand using `equals`; writing an overriding `equals` method is outside the exam scope.\n\n### Practice\n\nSimplify:\n\n```java\n!(n < 0 || n > 100)\n```\n\nAnswer:\n\n```java\nn >= 0 && n <= 100\n```"
